parts:
You are extracting a UBX protocol message definition from u-blox PDF manual pages.

TARGET MESSAGE: UBX-NAV-PVT
Expected IDs from TOC: class_id=0x01, message_id=0x07

CRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS:
1. Extract ONLY the message named "UBX-NAV-PVT". Ignore any other messages visible.
2. The payload table shows fields in order. Extract them exactly as shown with correct byte offsets.
3. Verify field sizes match offset differences.

=== DATA TYPES ===

Scalar types (use EXACTLY these values):
- U1, U2, U4, U8 = Unsigned integers (1/2/4/8 bytes)
- I1, I2, I4, I8 = Signed integers - NOTE: "I" is capital letter i, NOT digit 1
- X1, X2, X4, X8 = Bitfields (use for flags, mask, status fields)
- R4, R8 = Floating point (4/8 bytes)
- CH = ASCII character (1 byte)

Array types: Use object format {"array_of": "U1", "count": N}
- Check Type column for "[N]" or "x N" notation
- Verify array size matches offset gap to next field

=== CHARACTER RECOGNITION WARNINGS ===

The PDF uses fonts where these characters look similar:
- "I" (letter i) vs "1" (digit one): Data types are I1, I2, I4 (not 11, 12, 14)
- "O" (letter o) vs "0" (digit zero): Message names like UBX-ODO use letter "O"

=== FIELD EXTRACTION ===

For each field extract:
- name: Exact field name from PDF (preserve camelCase)
- byte_offset: Integer from "Offset" column (0-indexed)
- data_type: UBX type or array object
- description: Field description text
- unit: Physical unit if shown (ms, deg, m/s, etc.)
- scale: If scaling factor shown, include {"raw": "1e-7", "multiplier": 1e-7}
- reserved: Set true for reserved fields
- bitfield: For X-type fields with bit definitions, extract structure

=== ARRAY DETECTION (CRITICAL) ===

Common extraction error: missing arrays. Check carefully:
- Type column shows: "U1[6]", "U1 x 6", "CH[30]" = array
- Offset gaps reveal arrays: offset 4 to 8 with U1 = 4-byte array
- Reserved fields often span multiple bytes

=== BITFIELD DETECTION (CRITICAL) ===

Use X1/X2/X4 (NOT U1/U2/U4) when:
- Field named "flags", "mask", "status", "cfg", "supported", "enabled"
- Description mentions "bitfield" or lists bit meanings
- Sub-table shows bit positions

Extract bitfield structure for ALL X-type fields:
{"bits": [{"name": "bitName", "bit_start": 0, "bit_end": 0, "description": "..."}]}

=== PAYLOAD LENGTH ===

- Fixed: {"fixed": 28}
- Variable: {"variable": {"base": 8, "formula": "8 + N*12", "min": 8}}

=== REPEATED GROUPS (CRITICAL) ===

Many UBX messages contain repeated blocks of fields. Look for:
- "N x ..." or "numXxx x ..." patterns in the payload table
- Fields that repeat based on a count field (e.g., numSvs, numCh)
- Variable-length payloads with repeating structures

Extract repeated groups as:
{"repeated_groups": [{
  "name": "groupName",
  "repetition_type": "count_field",
  "count_field": "numSvs",
  "group_size_bytes": 12,
  "base_offset": 8,
  "fields": [...]
}]}

Common patterns:
- INF messages: Have a "str" repeated group for variable-length text
- NAV-SAT, NAV-ORB: Have satellite blocks repeated per numSvs
- MON-RXBUF: Has pending[] arrays per port

=== MESSAGE TYPE ===

Determine from context:
- "periodic" or "periodic_polled": Output messages sent automatically or on poll
- "input": Messages sent TO the receiver
- "output": Messages sent FROM the receiver  
- "command": One-shot commands
- "get"/"set"/"get_set": Configuration messages
- "poll_request": Poll request (usually empty payload)

=== SPECIAL MESSAGE TYPES ===

**UBX-INF-* (INF-DEBUG, INF-ERROR, INF-NOTICE, INF-WARNING, INF-TEST):**
- These contain a variable-length ASCII string payload
- Extract a single field named "str" with data_type {"array_of": "CH", "count": "variable"}
- Use repeated_groups with repetition_type "fill_remaining" for the string
- Do NOT return empty fields array

**UBX-MGA-* (Multiple GNSS Assistance):**
- Often have MULTIPLE SUB-TYPES on same pages (EPH, ALM, IONO, etc.)
- Each sub-type has different "type" field value and different payload
- Extract ONLY the sub-type matching the message name
- If name includes sub-type (e.g., "UBX-MGA-GPS-EPH"), extract only that

**UBX-LOG-FINDTIME:**
- Has TWO structures: INPUT (request) and OUTPUT (response)
- INPUT: version, type, year, month, day, hour, minute, second, reserved
- OUTPUT: version, type, reserved, entryNumber
- Extract based on message name suffix (-INPUT or -OUTPUT)

**UBX-RXM-RLM:**
- Has SHORT (16 bytes, type=0x01) and LONG (28 bytes, type=0x02) variants
- Extract based on message name suffix (-SHORT or -LONG)

**UBX-RXM-PMREQ:**
- V0 (8 bytes): duration, flags - NO version field
- V1 (16 bytes): version, reserved0[3], duration, flags, wakeupSources
- Extract based on suffix (-V0 or -V1)

=== QUALITY CHECKS ===

Before returning, verify:
- Byte offsets are sequential and non-overlapping
- Field sizes match offset gaps (offset 4 to 8 = 4 bytes)
- Total field sizes match payload length
- All fields from the payload table are included
If any of these appear to fail, you should review your initial extraction and re-extract the message.



=== MESSAGE NAME FORMAT (CRITICAL) ===

The "name" field MUST be EXACTLY "UBX-NAV-PVT" with NO modifications:
- Do NOT add descriptions like "(Poll request)" or "(Version 0)"
- Do NOT add suffixes like "Request" or "Poll"
- Do NOT include any parenthetical text
- Use ONLY the canonical message name: "UBX-NAV-PVT"

=== OUTPUT FORMAT ===

Return a JSON object with this structure:
{
  "name": "UBX-NAV-PVT",
  "class_id": "0xNN",
  "message_id": "0xNN",
  "description": "Short description",
  "message_type": "output",
  "payload": {
    "length": {"fixed": N} or {"variable": {...}},
    "fields": [
      {
        "name": "fieldName",
        "byte_offset": 0,
        "data_type": "U4",
        "description": "...",
        "unit": "ms",
        "scale": {"raw": "1e-7", "multiplier": 1e-7},
        "bitfield": {"bits": [...]}
      }
    ],
    "repeated_groups": [...]
  }
}

Extract the message completely and accurately.

fields.name: iTOW
fields.description: GPS time of week of the navigation epoch. See section iTOW timestamps in the integration manual for details.

bits.name: validDate
bits.description: 1 = valid UTC Date (see section Time validity in the integration manual for details)

bits.name: validTime
bits.description: 1 = valid UTC time of day (see section Time validity in the integration manual for details)

bits.name: fullyResolved
bits.description: 1 = UTC time of day has been fully resolved (no seconds uncertainty). Cannot be used to check if time is completely solved.

fields.name: fixType
fields.description: GNSSfix Type: 0 = no fix, 1 = dead reckoning only, 2 = 2D-fix, 3 = 3D-fix, 4 = GNSS + dead reckoning combined, 5 = time only fix

bits.name: gnssFixOK
bits.description: 1 = valid fix (i.e within DOP & accuracy masks)

bits.name: psmState
bits.description: Power save mode state (see Power management section in the integration manual for details. 0 = PSM is not active, 1 = Enabled (an intermediate state before Acquisition state, 2 = Acquisition, 3 = Tracking, 4 = Power Optimized Tracking, 5 = Inactive)

bits.name: headVehValid
bits.description: 1 = heading of vehicle is valid, only set if the receiver is in sensor fusion mode

bits.name: carrSoln
bits.description: Carrier phase range solution status: 0 = no carrier phase range solution, 1 = carrier phase range solution with floating ambiguities, 2 = carrier phase range solution with fixed ambiguities (not supported for protocol versions less than 20.00)

bits.name: confirmedAvai
bits.description: 1 = information about UTC Date and Time of Day validity confirmation is available (see section Time validity in the integration manual for details). This flag is only supported in Protocol Versions 19.00, 19.10, 20.10, 20.20, 20.30, 22.00, 23.00, 23.01, 27 and 28.

bits.name: confirmedDate
bits.description: 1 = UTC Date validity could be confirmed (see section Time validity in the integration manual for details)

bits.name: confirmedTime
bits.description: 1 = UTC Time of Day could be confirmed (see section Time validity in the integration manual for details)

fields.name: numSV
fields.description: Number of satellites used in Nav Solution

fields.name: headAcc
fields.description: Heading accuracy estimate (both motion and vehicle)

bits.name: invalidLlh
bits.description: 1 = Invalid lon, lat, height and hMSL (applicable to heading products only)

bits.name: lastCorrectionAge
bits.description: Age of the most recently received differential correction: 0 = Not available, 1 = Age between 0 and 1 second, 2 = Age between 1 (inclusive) and 2 seconds, 3 = Age between 2 (inclusive) and 5 seconds, 4 = Age between 5 (inclusive) and 10 seconds, 5 = Age between 10 (inclusive) and 15 seconds, 6 = Age between 15 (inclusive) and 20 seconds, 7 = Age between 20 (inclusive) and 30 seconds, 8 = Age between 30 (inclusive) and 45 seconds, 9 = Age between 45 (inclusive) and 60 seconds, 10 = Age between 60 (inclusive) and 90 seconds, 11 = Age between 90 (inclusive) and 120 seconds, >=12 = Age greater or equal than 120 seconds

bits.name: authTime
bits.description: Flag that indicates if the output time has been validated against an external trusted time source. 0 = Time is not authenticated, 1 = Time is authenticated

bits.name: nmaFixStatus
bits.description: Flag assigned to a fix that has been computed mixing satellites with data authenticated through Navigation Message Authentication (NMA) methods and satellites using unauthenticated data. The fix is flagged as Verified when internal cross-checks validates the unauthenticated signals against the authenticated ones. Note that Not Verified status does not imply directly spoofing attacks, to identify spoofing alerts refer to UBX-SEC-SIG. 0 = Not Verified: The mixed solution does not agree with the NMA authenticated data or the comparison could not be performed, e.g., not enough authenticated SVs to extrapolate the result or cryptographic data not decoded yet, 1 = Verified: The mixed solution agrees with the NMA authenticated data. Currently, the only existing NMA method is Galileo Open Service Navigation Message Authentication (OSNMA) protocol.

fields.name: headVeh
fields.description: Heading of vehicle (2-D), this is only valid when headVehValid is set, otherwise the output is set to the heading of motion

fields.name: magDec
fields.description: Magnetic declination. Only supported in ADR 4.10 and later.

fields.name: magAcc
fields.description: Magnetic declination accuracy. Only supported in ADR 4.10 and later.
